If you're as stingy as you say, your best bet is looking around for old workstations that are being sold for cheap by offices that are upgrading. Some are outright throwing them out, so you can score one for free if you live in the right area. Make sure you get something that's not unlike something built from off the shelf parts, meaning there's no proprietary shit like connectors, no BTX mobo and whatnot. You will want your GPU to fit into the case in its typical position.

If you're buying new, a good idea would be to get a great 500 series AMD mobo, a cheaper CPU like the 3600 and waiting for a cheap 5800X3D (or maybe a 12 or 16 core) to pop up somewhere down the line. You want the mobo to be more than good enough to power these potential upgrades. The problem with this approach is that ideally, you want to buy fast RAM for this setup, probably 32GB of it to future-proof it. This will cost a lot, but prices might come down as DDR5 gains popularity.
